<p>It seems to me that a user of a weblog software package will know HTML but the chances are much smaller a user will know a recently-invented meta-language.</p>

<p>Plus, HTML is a widely accepted standard that is useful in other contexts, whereas a new metalanguage only has one application (so far, granted).</p>

<p>If the user has a choice of learning something that is applicable one place and something that is applicable many places, wouldn&#8217;t they opt for learning something applicable in many places?</p>

<p>HTML&#8217;s b, i, img, a href, h2, h3, p, br tags are all one really needs, and it doesn&#8217;t seem that hard to wrap things in &lt; and >&#8230;</p>

